e source is the spell itself. For example, Burn Trail says “Burn Trail deals 3 damage to target creature or player.”',34069),('If an ability is causing damage to be dealt, that ability will always identify the source of the damage. The ability itself is never the source. However, the source of the ability is often the source of the damage. For example, Knollspine Invocation’s ability says “Knollspine Invocation deals X damage to target creature or player.”',34070),('If the source of the damage is a permanent, Swans of Bryn Argoll checks who that permanent’s controller is at the time that damage is prevented. If the permanent has left the battlefield by then, its last known information is used. If the source of the damage is a spell, its controller is obvious. If the source of the damage is a card from some other zone (such as a cycled Gempalm Incinerator), Swans of Bryn Argoll checks its owner rather than its controller.',34071),('If a creature with wither would deal damage to Swans of Bryn Argoll, that damage is treated just like any other damage. It’s prevented, and the creature’s controller draws cards. Swans of Bryn Argoll doesn’t get any -1/-1 counters.',34072),('If used on an Aura and the permanent enchanted by that Aura phases out, the Aura will not phase out. It will stay on the battlefield and then immediately be put into the graveyard since the permanent it was enchanting is phased out.',34073),('If the creature’s power is less than 0, use its actual value to determine the total life loss. However, if this total is 0 or less, no life is lost. For example, if Phthisis destroys a -2/3 creature, its controller would lose 1 life. If it destroys a -4/3 creature, its controller would lose no life.',34074),('The sacrifice is a triggered ability and not a cost.',34075),('When Kjeldoran Dead’s enters-the-battlefield ability resolves, if you don’t control any other creatures, you must sacrifice Kjeldoran Dead itself.',34076),('You can sacrifice zero mountains to deal zero damage.',34077),('You sacrifice the mountains during resolution.',34078),('Mortician Beetle’s ability triggers whenever any player, including you, sacrifices a creature because some other spell, ability, or cost instructed the player to do so. Mortician Beetle itself doesn’t allow you to sacrifice any creatures.',34079),('If you Donate an Aura, it stays where it is, but the targeted player now controls it.',34080),('You sacrifice the permanents before Shimatsu enters the battlefield, so you can’t sacrifice any creatures that enter the battlefield at the same time it does.',34081),('If it enters the battlefield as the only targetable creature, it must target itself.',34082),('When Momentary Blink resolves, the creature is exiled, then immediately returned to the battlefield. The game sees the returning card as a different permanent from the one that left the battlefield. Any counters, Auras, and so on are removed. Any spells or abilities targeting the creature no longer target it.',34083),('Any “as this enters the battlefield” choices for the affected creature are made by its owner, not its old controller.',34084),('If Momentary Blink is cast on a token creature, the token will not return to the battlefield, because of the rule that says a token that leaves the battlefield can’t come back.',34085),('Widespread Panic’s ability is put onto the stack after the library is shuffled.',34086),('This ability affects all creatures, not just the ones you control.',34087),('The number of cards put into the graveyard is based on the number of lands you control when Dreadwaters resolves.',34088),('Although players may respond to the activated ability, they can’t respond to the paying of its costs. The creature card will already be exiled by the time any player could respond.',34089),('The Zombie creature token you put onto the battlefield will also get a +1/+1 counter.',34090),('Memory Lapse has a self-replacement effect that replaces the spell going to the graveyard befor