d with power greater than Grenzo’s power, it stays in your graveyard.',38287),('A token copy of Sprouting Phytohydra is created even if the damage dealt to Sprouting Phytohydra destroys it.',38288),('If a token copy of Sprouting Phytohydra is dealt damage, it will create another token copy.',38289),('If Cytoshape turns a creature into a copy of Sprouting Phytohydra, and that creature is dealt damage, the token that is put onto the battlefield is simply a copy of Sprouting Phytohydra. At the end of the turn, the Cytoshaped creature will revert back to what it was, but the token copying it will not.',38290),('The black creature that entered the battlefield can be chosen as the target of Shadow Alley Denizen\'s ability, but it won\'t be able to attack that turn unless it also has haste.',38291),('Shadow Alley Denizen can be chosen as the target of its own ability.',38292),('If the target creature dies that turn, Searing Blood will deal 3 damage to whoever controls the creature when it dies, who isn’t necessarily the player who controlled it when Searing Blood resolved. It doesn’t matter what causes the creature to die.',38293),('If you don\'t reveal three creature cards with different names, you\'ll simply shuffle your library (including any cards you revealed).',38294),('All players will see the card you put into your hand, if any.',38295),('You play the revealed card as part of the resolution of Djinn of Wishes’s ability. Timing restrictions based on the card’s type (such as creature or sorcery) are ignored. Other play restrictions are not (such as “Cast [this card] only during combat\").',38296),('If the revealed card is a spell, you may cast it only if you can choose legal targets for it. If you cast it, it’s put on the stack, then Djinn of Wishes’s ability finishes resolving. The spell will then resolve as normal, after players get a chance to cast spells and activate abilities.',38297),('If the revealed card is a land, you can play it only if it’s your turn and y