ping it for mana, you can still activate a loyalty ability of that planeswalker even though it’s tapped.',41583),('Becoming a land may cause other Auras to become illegally attached. These are put into their owner’s graveyard, and any Equipment attached to the land become unattached and remain on the battlefield. Counters on the land remain on it even if they don’t do anything.',41584),('The amount of life you gain is equal to the toughness of the creature as it last existed on the battlefield, not its toughness in the graveyard.',41585),('If Awaken the Sky Tyrant isn’t on the battlefield as its ability resolves, you can’t sacrifice it. You won’t get the Dragon in that case.',41586),('Awaken the Sky Tyrant will trigger once for each source an opponent controls that deals damage to you, but you can sacrifice it only once.',41587),('Because the ability is targeted, it is not a mana ability. It can only be activated when you have priority, and goes on the stack like other non-mana abilities.',41588),('The damage dealt by Hydra Omnivore as a result of its triggered ability is not combat damage (and doesn\'t cause the ability to trigger again).',41589),('While controlling another player, you can see all cards that player can see. This includes cards in that player\'s hand, face-down cards that player controls, his or her sideboard, and any cards in his or her library that he or she looks at.',41590),('You can’t make the affected player concede. That player may choose to concede at any time, even while you’re controlling him or her.',41591),('You can’t make any illegal decisions or illegal choices—you can’t do anything that player couldn’t do. You can’t make choices or decisions for that player that aren’t called for by the game rules or by any cards, permanents, spells, abilities, and so on. If an effect causes another player to make decisions that the affected player would normally make (such as Master Warcraft does), that effect takes precedence. In other words, if the affected player wouldn’t make a decision, you wouldn’t make that decision on his or her behalf.',41592),('You only control the player. You don’t control any of his or her permanents, spells, or abilities.',41593),('If the target player skips his or her next turn, you’ll control the next turn the affected player actually takes.',41594),('You could gain control of yourself using Worst Fears, but unless you do so to overwrite someone else’s player-controlling effect, this doesn’t do anything.',41595),('If for some reason you can’t win the game (because your opponent controls Platinum Angel, for example), you won’t lose for having tried to draw a card from a library with no cards in it, because the draw was still replaced.',41596),('If you activate Chandra Ablaze\'s first ability, you don\'t discard a card until the ability resolves. You may activate the ability even if your hand is empty. You choose a target as you activate the ability even if you have no red cards in hand at that time.',41597),('As the first ability resolves, nothing happens if your hand is empty. But if you have any cards in hand, you must discard one. If you discard a nonred card, Chandra doesn\'t deal any damage.',41598),('If the creature targeted by the first ability is an illegal target by the time it resolves, the entire ability is countered. You won\'t discard a card.',41599),('You may activate Chandra\'s second ability even if your hand is empty. As it resolves, a player whose hand is empty simply draws three cards.',41600),('You cast red instant cards and red sorcery cards from your graveyard as part of the resolution of Chandra Ablaze\'s third ability. You don\'t choose which ones to cast until you\'re actually doing so as the ability resolves. You cast only the ones you want to, and you may cast them in any order. Timing restrictions based on the card\'s type (if it\'s a sorcery) are ignored. Other restrictions are not (such as \"Cast [this card] only during combat\"). Each card you cast t