get, even when the ability triggers during another player’s upkeep.',43724),('You can choose not to find the card.',43725),('If the creature was only a creature as the result of an animation effect, its controller still gets to search for a card with the same name. For example, if an animated Still Life is put into a graveyard, its controller gets to search his or her library for a card named Still Life.',43726),('This is the timeshifted version of Dwarven Thaumaturgist.',43727),('You draw two cards, then put one back as part of the same effect. You can’t do anything in between. Anything that triggers off of card drawing will wait until you finish resolving this ability before going on the stack.',43728),('The loss of life is simultaneous. If this causes both players to end up at 0 or less life, the game will be a draw. In a multiplayer game, players with 0 or less life will lose the game.',43729),('The cards put into hands this way are not “drawn.” For example, you couldn’t reveal a card with miracle put into your hand this way (but it also won’t count as the first card you’ve drawn this turn either).',43730),('Harabaz Druid\'s activated ability is a mana ability, so it doesn\'t use the stack and players can\'t respond to it.',43731),('You gain 4 life whether or not the targeted spell’s controller pays {4} and whether or not the targeted spell is countered.',43732),('Removing the other Dragon card from your graveyard has no effect on Scion of the Ur-Dragon.',43733),('When Scion of the Ur-Dragon becomes a copy of another Dragon, it loses its copy ability for the rest of the turn.',43734),('Only permanents still on the battlefield when Phyrexian Obliterator’s triggered ability resolves can be sacrificed.',43735),('Orzhov Charm\'s first mode doesn\'t target any of the Auras attached to the target creature.',43736),('If you choose the first mode, any Aura controlled by another player attached to the creature will be put into its owner\'s graveyard as a state-based action after the creature leaves the battlefield.',43737),('If you choose the second mode, you\'ll lose life equal to the creature\'s toughness when it was last on the battlefield.',43738),('For each of the modes, if the target creature or creature card is an illegal target when Orzhov Charm tries to resolve, it will be countered and none of its effects will happen.',43739),('If you choose the second mode, and Orzhov Charm resolves but the creature isn\'t destroyed (perhaps because it has indestructible or it regenerates), you\'ll still lose life equal to the creature\'s toughness.',43740),('Master of Cruelties isn\'t forced to attack, but if it does, it must do so alone. If you control another creature with an ability that says it must attack if able, that creature must attack and Master of Cruelties won\'t be able to.',43741),('If Master of Cruelties attacks alone, another creature entering the battlefield attacking will have no effect on it. Master of Cruelties continues to be an attacking creature. The other attacking creature will assign combat damage normally, regardless of whether Master of Cruelties\'s last ability triggers.',43742),('Master of Cruelties\'s last ability won\'t trigger if it attacks a planeswalker.',43743),('For a player\'s life total to become 1, what actually happens is that the player loses (or in some rare cases, gains) the appropriate amount of life. For example, if the player\'s life total is 4 when the last ability resolves, it will cause that player to lose 3 life. Other effects that interact with life loss (or gain) will interact with this effect accordingly.',43744),('Assigning no combat damage isn\'t the same as preventing that damage. Effects that make damage unpreventable will have no effect if no combat damage can be assigned.',43745),('This ability will only trigger if the player controls more lands at the beginning of upkeep. This condition is checked again at the start of resolution, and if not true, then nothing happens.',43746)