urn, it won\'t be affected.',44025),('If a creature changes controllers later in the turn, that won\'t change how Unnerving Assault affected it.',44026),('You must target a creature card in your graveyard and a creature on the battlefield to cast Foul Renewal. If the creature becomes an illegal target before Foul Renewal resolves, you’ll still return the creature card to your hand. If the creature card in your graveyard becomes an illegal target, the creature on the battlefield will be unaffected as there is no “card returned this way.”',44027),('Curse of Inertia’s ability will trigger only once per attacking player per combat phase, no matter how many creatures that player attacks with.',44028),('Even though the attacking player chooses the target of the ability, the ability is still controlled by the player who controls Curse of Inertia. Notably, a creature with hexproof controlled by the player who controls Curse of Inertia could be chosen, even though another player may be choosing the target.',44029),('As Blood is resolving, if only one of the targets is legal, Blood will still resolve but will have no effect: If the first target is illegal, it can\'t deal damage to anything. If the second target creature or player is illegal, it can\'t be dealt damage.',44030),('The amount of damage dealt is based on the first target creature\'s power as Blood resolves.',44031),('If the spell was colorless (an artifact), this card does not get any form of Protection.',44032),('The ability is cumulative. For example, if you control two Brago’s Representatives, you’ll vote three times per vote.',44033),('You make all your votes at the same time. Players who vote after you will know all of your votes when making their own.',44034),('The ability only affects spells and abilities that use the word “vote.” Other cards that involve choices, such as Archangel of Strife, are unaffected.',44035),('Players may not respond to the paying of costs. Once Burn at the Stake has been announced 