 target of that spell has somehow become illegal itself.',44057),('If you cast Ricochet Trap targeting a spell that targets a spell on the stack (like Cancel does, for example), you can\'t change that spell\'s target to itself. You can, however, change that spell\'s target to Ricochet Trap. If you do, that spell will be countered when it tries to resolve because Ricochet Trap will have left the stack by then.',44058),('If a spell targets multiple things, you can\'t target it with Ricochet Trap, even if all but one of those targets have become illegal.',44059),('If a spell targets the same player or object multiple times, you can\'t target it with Ricochet Trap.',44060),('The creatures are tapped during spell resolution.',44061),('The color of creature to be tapped is set when the effect is announced and even if you use Sleight of Mind after that, you can’t change what color creature needs to be tapped to prevent the destruction.',44062),('A player can choose zero or one Plains if they want.',44063),('You must choose two different colors.',44064),('Seal of the Guildpact’s last ability doesn’t change the mana cost or converted mana cost of any spell. It changes only the total cost you pay.',44065),('Seal of the Guildpact’s last ability can’t reduce the amount of colored mana you pay for a spell. It reduces only the generic component of that cost.',44066),('The cost reduction can apply to alternative costs such as evoke costs.',44067),('If a spell you cast has {X} in its mana cost, you choose the value of X before calculating the spell’s total cost. For example, if that spell’s mana cost is {X}{R}{G} and you’ve chosen red and green, you could choose 5 as the value of X and pay {3}{R}{G} to cast the spell.',44068),('Whenever you cast an artifact spell, Golem Foundry\'s first ability triggers and goes on the stack on top of it. It will resolve before the artifact spell does.',44069),('Only creatures you control when Spare from Evil resolves will be affected. Creatures that enter the battlefield or that you gain control of later in the turn won’t be.',44070),('A “non-Human creature” is any creature that doesn’t have the creature type Human. A creature that is a Human in addition to other creature types is not a non-Human creature.',44071),('Multiple instances of deathtouch on the same creature provide no additional benefit. A creature dealt damage by a creature with multiple instances of deathtouch is destroyed only once.',44072),('You must target two creatures as you cast Fulgent Distraction. If you can\'t (because there\'s just one creature on the battlefield, perhaps), you can\'t cast the spell.',44073),('Fulgent Distraction can target tapped and/or unequipped creatures.',44074),('If one of the targeted creatures is an illegal target by the time Fulgent Distraction resolves, that creature won\'t become tapped and no Equipment will be unattached from it. The other creature will still be affected. If both of the targeted creatures are illegal targets by the time Fulgent Distraction resolves, the spell is countered.',44075),('The Cauldron counts only mana spent on it. It doesn’t see the value of X, so isn’t affected by cost reductions. Thus, if you spent {C}{C}{R}{R} on X, you get {C}{C}{R}{R} later even if X was 6.',44076),('Cards which are not actually in your hand can’t be exiled by the Ice Cauldron.',44077),('If multiple cards are exiled by the Cauldron, the mana can only be used for the card that was exiled by the Cauldron when the most recent charge counter was put there.',44078),('The mana put in the Cauldron can only be used to cast the given spell, but you can add additional mana to a spell. This means you can pay part of the cost on one turn and the rest of it on the next turn.',44079),('You do not have to use any mana from the Cauldron when casting the spell if you don’t want to. You don’t even have to tap the Cauldron and draw the mana, you can just cast the spell using mana from somewhere else.',44080),('If multiple cards are exiled by the Cauldron, any one of them can be cast.',44081),('If the ability to exile a card with the Cauldron is countered, you do not lose the card since it is exiled during resolution.',44082),('It is possible to have more than one card exiled by the Cauldron. You can tap the Cauldron to remove the charge counter and whatever mana is on it but leave the card there. Later, you can tap it and put in mana and a charge counter to add another card.',44083),('X can be zero. This places a zero mana counter on the Cauldron.',44084),('You can only cast the spell when you could legally cast it normally. So no casting a sorcery on your opponent’s turn.',44085),('The mana can be used to pay for additional costs to cast the spell.',44086),('If the Cauldron leaves the battlefield, you can still cast any cards it exiled as though they were in your hand. You just no longer have access to the mana you charged the Cauldron with.',44087),('Tapping the Cauldron for the mana is a mana ability.',44088),('Produces mana of the last type used to put a counter on itself, not via any other charge counters.',44089),('In Limited formats (including Conspiracy Draft), the minimum deck size is generally 40 cards. With Advantageous Proclamation, your Conspiracy Draft deck must contain at least 35 cards.',44090),('The effect of Advantageous Proclamation is cumulative. If you have two in your command zone to start the game, your minimum deck size is reduced by ten, and so on.',44091),('If Veiling Oddity is suspended, then when the last time counter is removed from it, both its triggered ability and the “cast this card” part of the suspend ability will trigger. They can be put on the stack in either order.',44092),('Regardless of which order those abilities resolve in, Veiling Oddity can’t be blocked that turn. The ability affects all creatures, not just the creatures that were on the battlefield when it resolved.',44093),('If Veiling Oddity is suspended and the last time counter is removed